<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fewer Residents Emigrate Overseas in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502043194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0424 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1502043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hong Kong, February 15 (XINHUA) -- The number of 
emigrants from Hong Kong to Western countries dropped by almost 
20 percent in 1993 in spite of a prediction of higher proportion 
of emigration as 1997 approaches. 
  According to government provisional figures, 54,000 local 
residents left Hong Kong for overseas last year, putting the 
emigration figure below 60,000 for the first time in more than 
four years. 
  "The largest factor in the drop was the relatively poor 
economies of the most popular destination countries," said 
Acting Deputy Secretary for Security Keith Kwok. 
  On the contrary, he added, "the Hong Kong economy is still 
developing and growing while some who have emigrated have found 
it difficult to find work abroad." 
  Statistics showed only 5,925 were able to emigrate to 
Australia from July 1992 to July 1993, down from 13,000 between 
July 1991 to July 1992. 
  There was also a decrease in the number of people emigrating 
to the United States: 13,142 in 1993 against 14,882 in 1992. 
  But emigration to Canada rose to 31,200 in 1993 from 29,900 
in 1992. 
  Over the past few years, Canada, the United States and 
Australia were regarded as the favorite destinations of 90 
percent of Hong Kong emigrants. Most of those leaving the 
territory were young professionals, 30 to 40 years old. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

