<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Two-Way Trade With Chile Reaches $720 Million in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502072294 Taipei CNA in English 0635 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1502072294 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Edward Chen] </F>
  [Text] Buenos Aires, Feb. 14 (CNA) -- Two-way trade between 
Taiwan and Chile reached US$720 million in 1993, according to 
statistics compiled by the Economic Section of the Taipei 
Economic and Cultural Office in Chile. 
  Chile exported US$484.7 million worth of goods to Taiwan 
last 
year, while imports totaled US$225.6 million, leaving a trade 
surplus of US$179.1 million in Chile's favor, the statistics 
showed. 
  Copper, seafood, fish powders, lumber, pulp and fruits were 
Chile's main exports to Taiwan, while imports consisted of 
textiles, electric equipment, machinery, computers, bicycles, 
auto and bicycle parts, and fishing nets. 
  Taiwan was Chile's number two trade partner in Asia during 
the period, and Chile was Taiwan's number two trade partner in 
South America, the statistics revealed. 

</TEXT>

