<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Council Predicts Rise in Personal Incomes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1502022094 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1002 GMT 
14 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1502022094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 14 (CNS)--According to 
predictions by relevant departments under the State Council, the 
income of urban residents in the country will continue to grow 
in coming years with their capita income for living expenses in 
1995 expected to be RMB 2,933 [renminbi], up from RMB 2,225 in 
1993, an increase of 21.86 percent over that in 1992 while the 
growth of their living expenses will remain lower than the 
growth of their income by one to three percent. 
  According to these predictions, there are several factors 
accounting for their growth of income. First, with the reform 
for enterprises having been carried on in an intensive way, the 
economic efficiency of enterprises will continue to rise and the 
income of staff and workers will undoubtedly increase. In 1993 
alone, the gross amount of wages for both staff and workers in 
the country in 1993 increased by 22.6 percent over that in 1992. 
  Second, with implementation of the scheme aimed at 
increasing 
wages for civil servants in government organs, payment to people 
working in enterprises and institutions will also increase, 
resulting in the growth of income. 
  Third, with the gradual improvement of the securities 
markets 
in the country, residents investing in stocks and bonds will 
keep increasing and their income from this sector will increase. 
  Fourth, people with a second job are increasing with their 
income earned from this additional source rapidly increasing. 
For this reason, the per capita income of urban residents for 
their living expenses will be up to RMB 2,577 in 1994 and RMB 
2,933 in 1995, respective increases of 15.3 percent and 13.8 
percent while the growth of their spending for living will be 
13.58 percent and 12.41 percent respectively in these two years, 
lower than the growth of income by one to three percentage 
points. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26845 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi031_n_94005" </HT>


